The NbTiVZr and NbTiV 2 Zr alloys showed good compressive ductility at all studied temperatures while the Cr-containing alloys showed brittle-to-ductile transition occurring somewhere between 298 and 873 K. Strong work hardening was observed in the NbTiVZr and NbTiV 2 Zr alloys during deformation at room temperature. The alloys had yield strengths of 1105 MPa and 918 MPa, respectively, and their strength continuously increased, exceeding 2000 MPa after $ 40% compression strain.
The CrNbTiZr and CrNbTiVZr alloys showed high yield strength (1260 MPa and 1298 MPa, respectively) but low ductility (6% and 3% compression strain) at room temperature.
The CrNbTiZr and CrNbTiVZr alloys showed high yield strength (1260 MPa and 1298 MPa, respectively) but low ductility (6% and 3% compression strain) at room temperature.

Among the studied alloys, the CrNbTiVZr alloy shows the most attractive elevated temperature properties (Table  1 ). In particular, at 1073 K and 1273 K it has s 0.2 ¼615 MPa and 256 MPa and the steady-state flow stress, s SS ¼512 MPa and 183 MPa, respectively.
The CrNbTiZr alloy has approximately half the strength of CrTiNbVZr at elevated temperatures: s 0.2 ¼300 MPa and 115 MPa at 1073 K and 1273 K, respectively.

The strengths of the NbTiVZr and NbTiV 2 Zr alloys decrease rapidly above 873 K and during deformation at 1273 K, s 0.2 and s SS of these alloys are in the range of 53-77 MPa. For example, after deformation at 1273 K the microhardness of NbTiVZr decreases from 3.3 GPa to 3.0 GPa.

Among the studied alloys, the CrNbTiVZr alloy shows the most attractive elevated temperature properties (Table  1 ). In particular, at 1073 K and 1273 K it has s 0.2 ¼615 MPa and 256 MPa and the steady-state flow stress, s SS ¼512 MPa and 183 MPa, respectively. For example, after deformation at 1273 K the microhardness of CrNbTiVZr decreases from 4.7 GPa to 4.4 GPa.

Deformation behavior at room temperature The produced refractory multi-principal element alloys have high yield strength and hardness at room temperature. NbTiVZr and NbTiV 2 Zr consist of disordered BCC phases with rather large grain sizes (about 500-600 mm) and their high hardness and strength, as well as their strong tendency to deformation strengthening (Fig.  1 ), are evidently due to solid-solution like strengthening  [6, 7] . The high tendency to deformation strengthening and the absence of brittle intermetallic phases are probably the main reasons of good ductility of these two alloys.
